<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
The species is sufficiently described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Verseveldt, J" journalOrPublisher="Amsterdam" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="69 - 171" title="Octocorallia from north-western Madagascar (Part IIIa-d)." volumeTitle="Proceedings Koninklijke Nederlandse Akademie van Wetenschappen" year="1973">Verseveldt (1973</bibRefCitation>
: 141). Here I present the holotype colony shape (Figure 33) and SEM images of its sclerites (Figures 34-35).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
The species mostly resembles 
<taxonomicName class="Anthozoa" family="Nephtheidae" genus="Litophyton" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Litophyton curvum" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="curvum">Litophyton curvum</taxonomicName>
but differs in having straight sclerites in the surface layer of the base of the stalk and very spiny, almost spheroidal, sclerites in the surface layer of the base of the stalk.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
RMNH Coel. 12966 and RMNH Coel. 14596 are misidentifications. The specimens have no rodlets on the adaxial side of the polyp, as is the case in 
<taxonomicName class="Anthozoa" family="Nephtheidae" genus="Litophyton" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Litophyton filamentosum" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="filamentosum">Litophyton filamentosum</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
